Symbols, Patterns, and Levels of Abstraction

You’re right that mathematics and language both operate through symbols and rules, but they emphasize different kinds of patterns.
	•	Mathematics tends to formalize relationships—quantities, structures, motion—using precise symbolic grammar.
	•	Language carries meaning, intention, emotion, and instruction. It can guide behavior (“run,” “build,” “stop”) and coordinate people.

Both follow grammars:

symbols + rules → structures → meaning/pattern

The difference is mainly how strict the grammar is and what it’s optimized for. Math’s grammar is extremely tight; natural language is flexible but ambiguous.

